Interesting - all tests pass! The header manipulation seems to work correctly in this simple case. But the bug report says it happens occasionally. Let me look more carefully at the bug description again:

The bug shows that `X-Spam-*` headers and `DKIM-Signature` appear **at the end of the message body**. These are headers added by plugins during the pipeline. 

Let me think about when this could occur. Perhaps the issue is when `add_header` is called but the `header_list` is **empty** at the time headers were parsed? Let me check:

Wait, let me re-read `add_data` in transaction.js:

```javascript
if (this.header_pos === 0 && (line[0] === 0x0a || (line[0] === 0x0d && line[1] === 0x0a))) {
    this.header.parse(this.header_lines)
    this.header_pos = this.header_lines.length
    this.found_hb_sep = true
```

When `header.parse(`) is called, the `header_list` gets populated. So `message_stream.headers` should have items after this point.

But wait - what if `header_lines` is empty when the EOH is found? Like a message with just `\r\n` and no headers? In that case, `header.parse([])` would do nothing, and `header_list` would remain `[]`. Then `add_header` would add to `header_list`, making it non-empty.

No, the bug message shows headers like `Return-Path`, `Delivered-To`, `Received`, etc. So headers are present.

Let me think about another scenario. What if the message is so large that spooling kicks in? In `MessageStream.prototype.#write`:

```javascript
if (this.#bufferMax !== -1 && this.total_buffered > this.#bufferMax)
    this.spooling = true
```

When spooling is active, data is written to disk. And the pipe reads from the disk file. But the constructor headers are still emitted from `this.headers` (the in-memory reference). So the appended headers should still be there.

Hmm, let me think about this differently. Let me look for where the `add_header` might add to the WRONG place. Let me look at `remove_header`:

```javascript
remove_header(key) {
    this.header.remove(key)
    if (this.header_pos > 0) this.reset_headers()
}
```

And `Header.remove`:
```javascript
remove(key) {
    key = key.toLowerCase()
    delete this.headers[key]
    delete this.headers_decoded[key]
    this._remove_more(key)
}

_remove_more(key) {
    const key_len = key.length
    for (let i = 0, l = this.header_list.length; i < l; i++) {
        if (
            this.header_list[i].substring(0, key_len + 1).toLowerCase() ===
            `${key}:`
        ) {
            this.header_list.splice(i, 1)
            return this._remove_more(key)
        }
    }
}
```

`_remove_more` modifies `header_list` (which is `message_stream.headers`). And then `reset_headers` updates `header_pos`.

Wait, I just realized something. Look at `reset_headers`:

```javascript
reset_headers() {
    const header_lines = this.header.lines()
    this.header_pos = header_lines.length
}
```

This gets the header lines and sets `this.header_pos` to their length. But `this.header_pos` is used in `add_data` to determine if we're in the header phase. Once `add_data` has completed and `end_data` is called, `header_pos` is no longer used. So `reset_headers` seems vestigial.

Wait — let me look more carefully. After `end_data`, the `message_stream` has `#endCalled = true`. When `pipe` is called, `doRead` executes. In `doRead`:

```javascript
if (emitCtorHeaders) {
    for (const h of this.headers) {
        source.write(Buffer.from(h.replace(/\r?\n/g, lineEndings)))
    }
    source.write(Buffer.from(lineEndings)) // EOH marker
}
```

Then the raw data:
```javascript
if (skipRawHeaders) {
    const skipper = new HeaderSkipper()
    // ...
}
```

This emits constructor headers first, then body (after skipping raw headers). But what if `HeaderSkipper` ALSO skips some of the body? Let me look at the `HeaderSkipper` once more:

```javascript
_transform(chunk, enc, cb) {
    if (this.#eohFound) {
        this.push(chunk)
        return cb()
    }
    // ... look for EOH
    while ((offset = indexOfLF(buf)) !== -1) {
        const line = buf.slice(0, offset + 1)
        buf = buf.slice(offset + 1)
        const isEoh = (line.length === 2 && line[0] === 0x0d && line[1] === 0x0a) || (line.length === 1 && line[0] === 0x0a)
        if (isEoh) {
            this.#eohFound = true
            if (buf.length > 0) this.push(buf)
            this.#remainder = Buffer.alloc(0)
            return cb()
        }
    }
    this.#remainder = buf
    cb()
}
```

After EOH is found, everything is pushed through. Before EOH is found, only header lines are skipped. The chunk might split the EOH. This seems correct.

OK let me think about this from a completely different angle. The bug says "Sometimes, appended headers aren't put in the right spot." What if the issue is in how the `Transaction` constructor creates the `message_stream`?

```javascript
this.message_stream = new message.stream(this.cfg, this.uuid, this.header.header_list)
```

And `MessageStream` constructor:
```javascript
constructor(cfg = {}, id, headers) {
    this.headers = headers ?? []
```

So `this.headers` is the same array as `this.header.header_list`. Both reference the SAME array. Good.

But what about the `reset_transaction()` method? If the transaction is reset and a new `message_stream` is created, does it get the new `header_list`?

Let me check:

